vokes racial resistance, and delegitimates and silences such resistance. Kim asserts that the Flatbush Boycott was part of a larger resurgence of Black Power activism in New York City, that Haitian immigrants mobilized out of overlapping transnational and racial identities, and that Korean Americans responded by launching a countermovement seeking to restore the status quo. Racial protests are inevitable, she says, as long as conditions of racial injustice prevail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxRelations with Korean Americans. 0aBlack nationalismzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aKorean AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aKorean AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300148107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300148107.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles